		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				I agree with Meyhem but disagree with the way he said it.  What's wrong with being civil? <br>  <br> EQ is a RPG, but that doesn't mean that you can't RP begging either.  I don't ever &quot;beg&quot; items or money. <br> I HAVE asked politely for buffs, and don't get upset when I'm turned down.   <br> I have freely given items to newbies (who didn't ask, or just almost got there butt whupped by a monster and could obviously use a leg up) just because, even though I could have sold said    item(s) to other newbies/merchants for more $.  I always need $ for spells, but I know how tough those first few levels can be when all you've got is a few copper pieces to rub together.  I figure what goes around comes around. (BTW, it did. Someone gave me 2 pieces of Split-Paw armor for my druid &lt;unasked for&gt; just the other day.)  I still pretty much consider myself a newbie, but at least I'm not broke. :)  (right now anyway) <br>  <br> At the same time, I have ALWAYS refused requests for $, and generally refuse beggars I don't know. <br> I have freely given away loot to strangers nearby that needed it more than me.  (For example, a monk needing a putrid rib bone for the headband quest that I really don't need)  I have frequently asked permission to loot a corpse when someone was camping NPC's for exp.  I usually get a yes answer.  I don't consider this begging.  If they say no, that's their perogative.  I'm not upset in the slightest.  They earned the kill after all, not me. <br>  <br> Politeness goes a long way.  Even so, I don't think it is right for someone to hang around the bank or city gates and beg /politely/ until they are loaded up with stuff before they kill their first large rat! <br>  <br> My 2cp, <br> Kidin on Tunare<p>

							

